🔧 1. Create or Prepare a GitHub Repo

Go to GitHub and:

Create a new repository (e.g., docs, documentation, etc.)
Add your Markdown (.md / .mdx) files

Example structure:

/docs
  ├── introduction.mdx
  ├── getting-started.mdx
mint.json
🔗 2. Connect Mintlify to GitHub
Log into Mintlify
Create a new project
Choose “Import from GitHub”
Authorize Mintlify to access your GitHub account
Select your repository

👉 Mintlify will now pull your docs directly from GitHub.

⚙️ 3. Configure mint.json

This is your main config file.

Example:

{
  "name": "My Docs",
  "navigation": [
    {
      "title": "Getting Started",
      "pages": ["introduction", "getting-started"]
    }
  ]
}
Controls sidebar navigation
Defines structure of your docs
🚀 4. Automatic Deployments

Once connected:

Every git push to your repo → triggers auto-deploy
No manual deployment needed
🔄 5. Local Development (Optional but Useful)

Install Mintlify CLI:

npm install -g mintlify

Run locally:

mintlify dev

This lets you preview docs before pushing.

🌿 6. Typical Workflow
Edit docs locally

Commit changes:

git add .
git commit -m "Update docs"
git push
Mintlify auto-updates your live docs site 🎉
💡 Tips
Use .mdx for interactive components
Keep file names clean (used in URLs)
Organize docs into folders for scalability
Use branches for staging (if needed)

